Differentiate roles and responsibilities of SOC L1, L2, and L3
Research Report
Author: Vineeth M
Date: 02-28-2026

1. Tier 1: SOC Analyst (L1) – Alert Monitoring & Triage
Main Role: 
First-level monitoring and alert handling.
Responsibilities:
Monitor SIEM dashboards and alerts.
Perform initial triage of alerts. 
Identify false positives. 
Escalate real threats to Tier 2.
Skills: 
Basic understanding of networking and security. 
Familiar with SIEM tools (e.g., Splunk, QRadar). 
Strong attention to detail.


2. Tier 2: Incident Responder (L2) – Deep Investigation & Response
Main Role: 
Main Role: Investigation and incident response.
Responsibilities: 
Analyze escalated alerts. 
Perform forensic analysis of logs, endpoints, network traffic. 
Confirm security incidents. 
Coordinate with IT to contain and mitigate threats. 

Skills: 
Strong knowledge of malware, exploits, lateral movement. 
Scripting/automation (Python, PowerShell). 
Use of tools like Wireshark, VirusTotal, etc.
3. Tier 3: Threat Hunter / SME (L3) – Advanced Analysis & Threat Hunting
Main Role: 
Advanced threat analysis and proactive security.

Responsibilities: 
Proactively hunt for undetected threats. 
Develop detection rules. 
Reverse engineer malware. 
Provide expert guidance to Tier 1 & 2.

Skills: 
Deep understanding of APTs, TTPs (MITRE ATT&CK). 
Threat intelligence integration. 
Advanced forensics and malware analysis.


4. SOC Manager
Main Role: 
Management and coordination of SOC operations.
Responsibilities:
Supervise SOC team members.
Provide technical guidance when required.
Hire, train, and evaluate staff.
Create and manage operational processes.
Review incident reports.
Develop crisis communication plans.
Manage SOC budget and financial aspects.
Support security audits.
Report to CISO or senior management.

Skills: 
Leadership and project management. 
Cybersecurity certifications (e.g., CISSP, CISM). 
Good understanding of compliance standards (ISO, NIST, etc.).
 Collaboration Between SOC Tiers for Effective Security Operations
Security Operations Center (SOC) teams work collaboratively using a tiered workflow where each level supports the next. This structured cooperation allows organizations to detect threats quickly, analyze them accurately, and respond efficiently to security incidents.

1. Tier 1 → Detection and Initial Handling
Tier 1 analysts act as the first line of defense.
        Collaboration role:
    • Continuously monitor security systems and tools.
    • Detect suspicious activities and security alerts.
    • Filter false positives to reduce workload for higher tiers.
    • Collect raw data and enrich alerts with context.
    • Document findings clearly.
    • Escalate verified or suspicious incidents to Tier 2.
                 ->Their work ensures that only meaningful threats move forward for deeper analysis.


2. Tier 2 → Investigation and Incident Response
Tier 2 analysts collaborate closely with Tier 1 by using the data collected during triage.
Collaboration role:
    • Review incidents escalated from Tier 1.
    • Perform in-depth analysis using threat intelligence.
    • Determine attack scope and affected systems.
    • Coordinate with IT and system teams to contain threats.
    • Develop remediation and recovery strategies.
    • Escalate highly complex incidents to Tier 3 when necessary.
    • Provide feedback to Tier 1 to improve alert accuracy.
                 -> They transform alerts into actionable security responses.

3. Tier 3 → Advanced Analysis and Strategic Improvement
Tier 3 analysts support both lower tiers and strengthen overall SOC capabilities.
Collaboration role:
    • Handle complex or sophisticated incidents escalated from Tier 2.
    • Perform advanced threat hunting and forensic investigations.
    • Identify hidden vulnerabilities and attack patterns.
    • Improve detection rules and monitoring tools.
    • Mentor Tier 1 and Tier 2 analysts.
    • Share threat intelligence and strategic recommendations.
                 ->Their expertise improves future detection and prevention across all tiers.

4. SOC Manager → Coordination and Oversight
The SOC Manager ensures collaboration works smoothly.
Collaboration role:
    • Coordinate communication between tiers.
    • Establish workflows and escalation procedures.
    • Review incident reports and performance.
    • Provide resources and training.
    • Communicate with executive management.
                 ->Ensures organized and efficient team operations

